\section{The Mandelbrot Set}

Now, with some of the basics out of the way, we can begin to tackle the Mandelbrot Set itself. As it was said at the beginning, the set is given when the funtion $f_{c}(z)=z^{2}+c$ does not diverge when iterated from 0. Which essentially means, for any given complex value for $c$, when used in the function, which iterates starting from $z=0$, if the summation of that iterative process \textit{converges}, then that number $c$ is in the Mandelbrot Set.

\subsection{Translating into Cartesian Coordinates}

The iteration is often noted as $f_{c}(0),f_{c}(f_{c}(0)),\dots$, but I found it very worthwhile to do the algebra and see this same iteration, but with $x$'s, $y$'s and $i$'s, because the complex plane is purely conceptual, the computer screen can only work with Cartesian coordinates. We are in fact substituting $c$ for an $(x, y)$ coordinate, but in the format $(x,y)=x+iy$.

\begin{align*}
    f_{c}(z) &= z^2 + c         &      &\\
    f_{x+iy}(0) &= 0^2 + (x_{c} + iy_{c}) & z&=0 & c&=x+iy\\
    f_{x+iy}(x+iy) &= (x+iy)^2 + (x_{c} + iy_{c}) & z&=\dots & c&=x+iy\\
    f_{x+iy}(x+iy) &= (x^2 + i2xy - y^2) + (x_{c} + iy_{c}) & z&=(x^2 + i2xy - y^2)& c&=x+iy
\end{align*}

Note that $i=\sqrt{-1}$ in the expansion of $z^2$. This is all the information we need to understand the iteration in terms of $x$ and $y$. With $x^2+i2xy-y^2+x_{c}+iy_{c}$ we can simply take the real numbers for the $x$ coordinate, and the imaginary numbers for the $y$.

\begin{align*}
    x &= x^2 - y^2 + x_{c} \\
    y &= i2xy + iy_{c}
\end{align*}

The size of a number in the complex plane can be understood by it's distance, or magnitude, from the origin. This can be found simply with Pythagoras' equation $a^2 = b^2 + c^2$. This is useful as a secondary test for whether a number is in the set or not as if at any point the value for $f_{c}(z) \geq 2$ then that number will surely diverge towards $\infty$. Any number with a magnitude which stays below 2, may or may not diverge, but this can be settled by the iteration limit.

\subsection{Implementing in Code}

In essence, any code implementation which visualises the Mandelbrot Set is done by first iterating through $(x,y)$ points in Cartesian space, and using the conversion above to put these values through the iterative process of the Mandelbrot series, to check whether this iterative process converges or diverges. We cannot iterate to infinity so we cap this process to a given number of iterations — if the function reaches the iteration limit OR if the magnitude of the number is $\geq$ 2 we can assume it is diverging and thus not in the set. But it is the possibility to iterate infinitely which allows for the potential to scale in to the visualisation and observe the fractal patterns formed.

