\lstinputlisting[language=JavaScript, caption=Mick Griersons implementation found on \href{https://mimicproject.com/code/fc4289ff-1691-44e8-9c36-8e9e71989ff9}{Mimic.com}]{mick_mandel.js}

First Mick iterates across every pixel in the canvas, which has been translated so that we can use all four quandrants of $(x,y)$ space. At each pixel we store the values as \verb|cx| and \verb|cy|. These values are also scaled to between -2 and 2, by dividing by \verb|width/4| (only \verb|width| is used as the canvas is square).

\begin{equation*}
    \frac{\frac{\pm width}{2}}{\frac{width}{4}} = \pm 2
\end{equation*}

On line 5 we then begin the iteration for $f_{c}(z)=z^2 +c$. At the beginning of each iteration we check if the value being tested is greater than 2, if it is not we proceed. Using the formulae determined above we get new values for \verb|x| and \verb|y| to pass into the next iteration. The only difference to the maths we have seen so far is that $i$ is ommited for the calculation of $y$. We have already differentiated between Real and Imaginary with the expansion of $z^2$ and we are now only dealing with Cartesian space, so the $i$ element can be igorned, and the $y$ coordinate effectively stands in as the imaginary number part of the complex number. The color for the pixel is then updated to a value which approches black as the number of iterations (\verb|test|) gets higher. Any pixel which is solid black is very likely to be in the set as it has reached the maximum iterations.



